@node introduction "Introduction"
The year is 1990 and a friend of mine (Johan Widingsjö) starts to program
on his very own BBS-system. He's programming on a slow XT running an early
version of MS-DOS. He wanted a multi-line system on a singletask OS. He
succeded.

My intrest for BBSes grew very fast and the summer 1990 I started my own
BBS, running an old american software with lots of limitations (no names).
I was not satisfied with that software, but at that time the only thing I
did on my Amiga 500 was stupid demos. I started to learn C, wrote a Snake-
game, and while thinking of the joy Johan had while making his system I was
discussing with Per Lindh how easy it would be to make a multi-line system
on the Amiga. Per agreed and suggested we should compete of who made the
best BBS-system on the Amiga. I thought the project would be too big for
me, who hardly could do anything in C. A few days later Per talked me into
it, and we started right away (Apr-91). He gave up a week later, but I
thought I should give it a few weeks more. Later on I was stuck with it, I
just couldn't put it away!

Early february 1992 I switched software to Rcn.

My users found bug after bug, and gave me suggestion after suggestion. It
became even more fun to work on it! It was (is) really nice to see peoples
reactions to the things I did (do)!

Early 1993 a found myself a beta-tester (Jonas Andersson). He encouraged me
to release Rcn, and the summer 1993 I finally did release a demo-version!

And now, 2.5 years later.

2.5 years might seem like a very long time to write a system like this. My
only comment is: I'm young. I'm not spending all my spare-time in front of
the computer, and I didn't need to rush.

Not very long after I started on Rcn, Johan did have an harddisk-crash and
all his BBS-sources was destroyed. Johan is now running Proboard but is always
saying that he wants to make an own system. We'll see what'll happen.

+ + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + +

When I started on Rcn I wanted a system that could be configured to look
like everything I could think of. I wanted an advanced system where I could
replace builtin things with my own, and it should be possible to control
it from the outside at as many different ways as possible. I wanted a stable
system that didn't crash when I left home, and did not freakout and mess
everything up.

Some people have helped me more than others to reach my goal:

Johan Widingsjö   -  Inspiration, helping me to solve problems.

Per Lindh         -  He started it all and have come with lots of
                     suggestions.

Dave McIntosh     -  Customized his FSEd for Rcn.

Anders Ĺsbrink    -  Not telling anyone what Reccoon actually means!
                     (I hope!!!)

Daniel Stenberg   -  His wonderful fpl.library! What would Rcn be
                     without FPL!?

Jonas Andersson   -  Beta-testing and lots of ideas.

Andreas Öman      -  Lots of ideas.

Kjell Ericson     -  His Frexx-patch program!

And some of my users. I think Andreas Zeccagno should be mentioned.
Everything he touches crashes, and he've found many bugs no-one could
possible find.

+ + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + +

- 950516 -

Big changes to the reccoon system, it changed owner and developer, from now
on, I (Henric Andersson) will be developning and releasing new versions.

My interest for reccoon started one day when a friend of mine had come across
a new bbs system called Reccoon. And after a while I was totally set on it, and
that's how my interest in this software started.

@endnode

